Functions Every Backend developerNo matter which backend framework I’m using — Node.js, Express, NestJS, Django, Laravel, or anything else — I always find myself writing the same utility functions.
They’re not tied to any specific framework, and they don’t solve complex business problems. Instead, they handle the small, repetitive tasks that show up in almost every project.
Having these utilities ready from day one saves time, keeps my codebase organized, and helps me avoid writing the same logic over and over again.
Here are the ten utility functions I consider essential for backend development.

1. Generate a Unique ID
Almost every application needs unique identifiers.
import crypto from "crypto";function generateId() {
return crypto.randomUUID();
}I use this for order IDs, file names, temporary tokens, and tracking requests.

2. Format Dates
Raw timestamps aren’t always user-friendly.
function formatDate(date) {
return new Date(date).toLocaleString("en-US", {
dateStyle: "medium",
timeStyle: "short",
});
}Whether you’re generating reports or sending emails, consistent date formatting makes a big difference.

3. Paginate Results
Large datasets should never be returned all at once.
function paginate(page = 1, limit = 10) {
const skip = (page - 1) * limit; return {
skip,
limit,
};
}This helper keeps pagination logic consistent across all endpoints.

4. Validate Required Fields
Checking request data is something every API does.
function validateFields(data, fields) {
return fields.every(field => data[field] !== undefined);
}Instead of repeating validation in every route, I centralize the logic.

5. Remove Empty Values
Cleaning request objects before storing them helps avoid unnecessary data.
function removeEmpty(obj) {
return Object.fromEntries(
Object.entries(obj).filter(
([, value]) => value !== null && value !== undefined
)
);
}This is especially useful before database updates.

6. Delay Execution
Sometimes a small delay is useful during development or testing.
function sleep(ms) {
return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}Example:
await sleep(1000);I mostly use this while testing background jobs or retry logic.

7. Create a Slug
Whenever I’m building blogs, e-commerce sites, or CMS platforms, I need clean URLs.
function slugify(text) {
return text
.toLowerCase()
.trim()
.replace(/\s+/g, "-")
.replace(/[^\w-]/g, "");
}Example:
"Learning Node.js Today"becomes
learning-nodejs-today
8. Retry Failed Operations
Network requests don’t always succeed on the first attempt.
async function retry(fn, attempts = 3) {
for (let i = 0; i < attempts; i++) {
try {
return await fn();
} catch (error) {
if (i === attempts - 1) throw error;
}
}
}This helper works well with external APIs that occasionally fail.

9. Standard API Response
Returning consistent responses makes frontend integration much easier.
function success(data, message = "Success") {
return {
success: true,
message,
data,
};
}function error(message) {
return {
success: false,
message,
};
}Every endpoint follows the same response structure, making debugging and documentation much simpler.

10. Log Execution Time
Performance issues are easier to spot when you measure them.
async function measure(label, fn) {
console.time(label); const result = await fn(); console.timeEnd(label); return result;
}Example:
await measure("Fetch Users", async () => {
return getUsers();
});It’s a simple way to identify slow database queries or API calls during development.

Why I Keep These Utilities
These functions aren’t complicated, but they eliminate a surprising amount of repetitive work.
Instead of rewriting validation, pagination, formatting, and response logic in every project, I keep a small utilities folder that I can reuse whenever I start something new.
It makes the codebase cleaner, reduces bugs, and lets me focus on building actual features rather than solving the same small problems repeatedly.

Final Thoughts
One thing I’ve learned after building backend applications is that productivity isn’t about writing more code — it’s about writing code you don’t have to write again.
A handful of well-designed utility functions can save hours over the lifetime of a project. They keep your API consistent, simplify maintenance, and make new features easier to build.
As you gain experience, you’ll naturally build your own toolkit of reusable helpers. Start small, improve them over time, and you’ll soon have a collection you can carry into every backend project.
